  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    The choice between Cigna Global and Aetna International fundamentally comes down to one question: <strong>how important is US healthcare access to you?</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>If you don't need US coverage</strong>—you've permanently relocated, rarely visit the US, and have no intention of getting US medical care—<strong>Cigna Global</strong> is often the better choice. Their worldwide-excluding-US pricing is competitive, their customer service is excellent, and their digital experience is superior. Families particularly appreciate Cigna's options.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>If you need US coverage</strong>—you visit home regularly, maintain US ties, want the option of US medical care, or may eventually repatriate—<strong>Aetna International</strong> is the clear winner. Their integrated US coverage avoids Cigna's expensive add-on, their US network access is seamless, and the potential savings are substantial. American expats who need US access should seriously consider Aetna.
  </p>
  <p>
    Both are excellent insurers backed by major American healthcare corporations. You won't go wrong with either for basic international coverage. But matching the right provider to your US coverage needs will save you money and provide a better experience.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our recommendation: Get quotes from both providers for your specific situation. Compare pricing with and without US coverage. The numbers will make the right choice clear.
  </p>

