  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is Cigna Global or Aetna International better for American expats?</h3>
  <p>
    It depends on your US coverage needs. Cigna is better for expats who don't need US healthcare access—their ex-US pricing is more competitive. Aetna is better for expats who need US coverage—their integrated approach is cheaper than Cigna's add-on model.
  </p>

  <h3>Why does Cigna charge so much more for US coverage?</h3>
  <p>
    US healthcare costs are dramatically higher than anywhere else in the world. Cigna prices their base plans for worldwide-excluding-US markets, then adds the US cost separately. Aetna builds US costs into their base pricing, which appears higher initially but is often cheaper for those who need US access.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I use Aetna International's US network like domestic US insurance?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes, largely. Aetna International integrates with Aetna's domestic US network. You can use the same providers, direct billing relationships work, and claims process similarly. It's not identical to domestic Aetna coverage but comes close.
  </p>

  <h3>Which provider has better customer service?</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is generally rated higher for customer service. Their representatives are consistently helpful and knowledgeable. Aetna's service is professional and competent but less frequently praised. If customer service is your top priority, Cigna has the edge.
  </p>

  <h3>What if I'm not sure whether I'll need US coverage?</h3>
  <p>
    If there's meaningful uncertainty, lean toward Aetna. Having US coverage you don't use costs less than adding it to Cigna later when you need it. Plus, adding coverage mid-policy may trigger new underwriting or limitations. <a href="/best/expat-health-insurance" class="text-primary-600 hover:text-primary-700 underline">Get quotes from both providers</a> to compare actual pricing for your situation.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I switch between these providers later?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes, you can switch at any annual renewal. However, conditions that developed while on your previous policy become pre-existing for the new insurer's underwriting. Switch carefully, especially if you've had health issues.
  </p>

